Source: Office International des Epizooties (OIE) Emergency Alert Messages
[edited]
<http://www.oie.int/Messages/040518SWZ.htm>


African horse sickness in Swaziland
-----------------------------------
The last outbreak of African horse sickness in Swaziland was reported to
the OIE in 1993. This information was received on (and dated) 17 May 2004
from Dr Robert S Thwala, director, Department of Veterinary and Livestock
Services, Ministry of Agriculture and Co-operatives, Mbabane:

Nature of diagnosis: clinical and postmortem. No samples taken for
laboratory examination.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 1 May 2004.
Date of diagnosis: 3 May 2004.
Estimated date of primary infection: 30 Apr 2004.

Location of the outbreak: Hhohho province (26o 27' 48.7" S - 31o 12' 43.9" E).
Description of affected population: the affected animal was imported from
South Africa on 30 Apr 2004. It had come for a show with vaccination
history for African horse sickness (AHS).

Total number of equids in the outbreak: 51.
Total number of cases/deaths: 1.
Source of agent/origin of infection: the affected animal is suspected to
have arrived from South Africa already infected.

Control measures:
- quarantine of farm
- remaining horses are being closely monitored. All horses on the farm are
vaccinated for AHS annually.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[African Horse Sickness can present a very striking picture clinically and
at necropsy. It appears as if this report is based on just such findings.
We have had several recent reports, and the disease is rather commonly
reported from Southern Africa. See African horse sickness - Zambia (OIE)
20040508.1251 below. - Mod.PC]
